Subject: Re: [T2] Engine install assistance please

On Tue, 15 Jan 2002, Karl wrote:

> Not necessary to remove the shifter. On bays, it is designed to pivot. And the
> axles hold the trans up along with the front rubber mount.

but be sure to remove the linkage bracket on an automatic before doing
this.

   on an automatic you don't need the clearance that a manual needs (no
long tranny shaft to clear the clutch plate) so I always recommend on an
auto to leave the tranny alone and just drop the engine

Bob

> 
> > Tom,
> >
> > What Karl suggests is SOP on the Vanagon engine removal.  I have not tried
> > it on a bay, but I see no reason it would not work.  One thing on the bay,
> > though... do remove the shift rod from the nose of the trans before you
> > swing the trans down!  If you don't, it will really bind on you! You also
> > need to support the bell housing lest it fall on the floor.  A couple 2x4s
> > should do it.
